<body>
<header>
    <h1>Case Study: Data Governance in Air Quality Data</h1>
    <p><strong>From Initial Collection to Final Analysis</strong></p>
</header>
<main>
    <section>
        <h2>1. Background & Objectives</h2>
        <p>
            Urban areas face growing air quality challenges. Effective data governance ensures air quality data is <strong>reliable, accessible, and actionable</strong> for policy, research, and public engagement.
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Objective:</strong> Develop a comprehensive data governance framework for urban air quality monitoring, ensuring data is FAIR (Findable, Accessible, Interoperable, Reusable) and high quality.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>2. Stakeholder Engagement</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Public Administration:</strong> Environmental agencies, city government</li>
            <li><strong>Researchers:</strong> Universities, scientists</li>
            <li><strong>Civil Society:</strong> NGOs, citizen groups</li>
            <li><strong>Business:</strong> Technology providers, industry</li>
            <li><strong>General Public:</strong> Residents, commuters</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            Multi-stage consultations identify needs, address privacy, access, and resolve conflicts early.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>3. Data Governance Framework Structure</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Ownership & Stewardship:</strong> Define data owners, managers, and accountability.</li>
            <li><strong>Access Rights:</strong> Set rules for viewing, using, or modifying data.</li>
            <li><strong>Quality Standards:</strong> Metrics for accuracy, timeliness, completeness, reliability.</li>
            <li><strong>Metadata & Provenance:</strong> Document sources, transformations, and quality checks.</li>
            <li><strong>Privacy & Security:</strong> Controls for sensitive data and regulatory compliance.</li>
            <li><strong>Interoperability:</strong> Use standard formats and APIs for data sharing.</li>
            <li><strong>Open Data Policies:</strong> Promote public access while balancing privacy and commercial interests.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>4. Implementation Workflow</h2>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Data Collection</strong>: Validated sensors, standard protocols, rich metadata.</li>
            <li><strong>Ingestion & Quality Control</strong>: Automated/manual checks, calibration, provenance tracking.</li>
            <li><strong>Integration & Standardization</strong>: Unified formats, harmonization across datasets.</li>
            <li><strong>Metadata Management</strong>: Comprehensive records for transparency.</li>
            <li><strong>Access Control & Security</strong>: Tiered access, privacy protection, compliance.</li>
            <li><strong>Dissemination</strong>: Dashboards, APIs, downloadable datasets.</li>
            <li><strong>Continuous Improvement</strong>: Annual reviews, stakeholder feedback, audits.</li>
        </ol>
        <div class="block">
            <strong>Sample Data Flow Diagram:</strong>
            <pre>
[Sensors] 
   ↓
[Data Ingestion & Quality Control] 
   ↓
[Integration & Standardization] 
   ↓
[Metadata & Provenance] 
   ↓
[Access Control & Open Data Portal] 
   ↓
[Analysis & Decision Support]
            </pre>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>5. Sample Documents</h2>
        <h3>5.1 Data Governance Policy (Excerpt)</h3>
        <div class="block">
            <strong>Purpose:</strong> Ensure responsible collection, management, sharing, and use of air quality data.<br>
            <strong>Scope:</strong> All air quality monitoring data from city sensors, third parties, and citizen science.<br>
            <strong>Key Policies:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Only validated sensors; mandatory metadata (time, location, device ID).</li>
                <li>Public: Aggregated, anonymized data; Researchers: Raw data with agreement; Internal: Full access.</li>
                <li>Daily automated checks; quarterly audits.</li>
                <li>All datasets must include provenance and quality metrics.</li>
                <li>No PII collected; public data aggregated to block level.</li>
                <li>Open data license (e.g., CC BY 4.0); API for real-time feeds.</li>
                <li>Annual policy review.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>5.2 Sample Metadata Record</h3>
        <table>
            <tr><th>Field</th><th>Value</th></tr>
            <tr><td>Dataset Name</td><td>Berlin Air Quality Monitoring 2025</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Owner</td><td>City Environmental Agency</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Source</td><td>Fixed stations, mobile sensors, crowdsourcing</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Period</td><td>Jan 2025 – Dec 2025</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Spatial Coverage</td><td>Berlin, Germany</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Quality Score</td><td>0.98 (validated)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Provenance</td><td>Sensor IDs, calibration logs, processing steps</td></tr>
            <tr><td>License</td><td>CC BY 4.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Last Updated</td><td>2025-07-10</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Access Level</td><td>Public (aggregated), Restricted (raw)</td></tr>
        </table>

        <h3>5.3 Data Quality Report (Excerpt)</h3>
        <div class="block">
            <strong>Completeness:</strong> 99.2% of expected records present.<br>
            <strong>Accuracy:</strong> 98.7% within calibration tolerance.<br>
            <strong>Timeliness:</strong> 100% available within 5 minutes.<br>
            <strong>Issues:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Sensor #A12 drifted; recalibrated 2025-05-15.</li>
                <li>0.3% data flagged as outliers, removed from public dataset.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>5.4 Data Sharing Agreement (Excerpt)</h3>
        <div class="block">
            <strong>Parties:</strong> City Environmental Agency & Research Institute<br>
            <strong>Purpose:</strong> Academic research only<br>
            <strong>Terms:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>No commercial use or re-identification attempts.</li>
                <li>Publication must acknowledge data source.</li>
                <li>Data security measures required.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>6. Final Output: Open Data Portal Example</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Live Map:</strong> Real-time PM2.5, NO2, O3 by district</li>
            <li><strong>Download:</strong> CSV, JSON, API for hourly data</li>
            <li><strong>Documentation:</strong> Data dictionary, sensor specs, quality methodology</li>
            <li><strong>Feedback:</strong> Public form for data issues or suggestions</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>7. Continuous Improvement</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Annual policy review and update</li>
            <li>Public engagement forums</li>
            <li>Pilot new data sources and update governance as needed</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

